Patch Set 10:

I don't know if this matters, but there seems to be something strange here.  qpid-python, that Sean added on PS10, is listed in test-req.txt, but doesn't show up when I create the l-c tox environment and then use its pip to do 'pip freeze' as described in Doug's email.  Also, my pip freeze output doesn't include pika or pika-pool, which are in the l-c.txt on this patch.

Patch Set 10:

> I don't know if this matters, but there seems to be something
 > strange here.  qpid-python, that Sean added on PS10, is listed in
 > test-req.txt, but doesn't show up when I create the l-c tox
 > environment and then use its pip to do 'pip freeze' as described in
 > Doug's email.  Also, my pip freeze output doesn't include pika or
 > pika-pool, which are in the l-c.txt on this patch.

All of those things are optional dependencies of oslo.messaging, only needed when specific drivers are used. I'm not sure why qpid-python isn't included here automatically. Do you want to add it? Is it used by the unit tests?

Patch Set 10:

I just realized that since the l-c uses basepython of python3 and the line in test-req.txt for qpid is:

qpid-python>=0.26;python_version=='2.7' 

it wouldn't get pulled in by pip.  On a related note, I removed it from test-req.txt and the py27 unit and functional tests still pass.  I'm going to put up a DNM patch without qpid to see what happens, there may be some cruft in my environment.

Patch Set 10:

Patch of current master without qpid-python in test-req.txt is https://review.openstack.org/559194

Patch Set 10: -Code-Review

That's really odd. If you go back and look at patchset 10, the failure there was that qpid-python was missing. If that was just a red herring, and it was actually whatever that was that appears to have been fixed indirectly with the matching u"" failure message, then I agree we should just remove that package.

Patch Set 10:

> @Doug: from https://review.openstack.org/559194 , looks like we
 > don't need qpid in test-requirements.txt.  Is your advice to not
 > include it, or to leave it in "just in case"?

If the unit tests don't import and use it, and you don't have a functional test job configured to use it, you shouldn't need it. And if you do have either of those things, you should be getting the version that oslo.messaging specifies as *its* dependency. So I would remove it from the file.
